a. Inconoinnity. Suetonius takes no pains to produce con· cinnity by means of figures of speech and rhetorical devices. Figurcs of rhetoric, comparatively speaking, seldom occur and ere sometimes not employed of set purpose. Inconcinnity is effeeted in various ways, even in the expression of correlative members:

proluitum ei siue frumento stipendioque operamini. 68.1 ; sive di einiius sice ulique conuciuru, dul. 1. 3 ; lucili ei ibidem statim, Aup. 39 ; in continentem lenioribusque punio condicionibus, Aac. 65. 3; ud decli nendum inuidiam elui . . . merendare, Jul. 4.1; in memorium . . .

vel quod . . . prospere cesserat, Anu. l. 1; imposne meniis un simulato dementia incertum, Aug. 19. 2.

b. Certain irregularities are noticeable in the position of individual words:

(1) The appositive before its noun, especially when it ex- presses official position or relationship:

dictatore Sulla, Jul. 1.1; collega eius Murcus Bibulus, Jul. 10.1; auunculus Guesur, Aug. 94. 9. (2) The adjective often precedes in proper names:

Mupni Alexandri, dul. 7.1 ; Magnum Pompeium, Aup. 4.1.

(3) The gentile name follows the cognomen: Calvi Licini, Jul. 49.1 ; Crispus Sallustius, Aup. 86. 3.

(4) Attributive words in unusual positions:

quattuor quibus in conspectum uenit ioris, Jul. 35. 2 ; plurium quum quisquam umquam dierum supplicationes, dul. 24.3; od ium insignem despecti senatus contumelium, Jul. 79. 1.
